a Scope that represents an EXPRESS SCHEMA, i.e. a collection of SchemaElement declarations and interface declarations.

the name of the EXPRESS schema.

the version identifier for the EXPRESS schema, if any.

a refinement of Scope.terms, represents the collection of terms that are defined in a Schema namespace.
a refinement of ScopedId.namespace, represents the relationship between a SchemaScopedId and the Schema that is its namespace.

any EXPRESS object that defines a namespace for the interpretation of identifiers.

See clause 10 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
A Scope that is neither a SCHEMA nor a NamedType. Terms defined in a LocalScope are not visible at the Schema level.

a NamedElement (EXPRESS model element) that can be defined in either a Schema or a LocalScope, and has (or may have) a unique identifier within that Scope. This is an artifact of the declaration and namespace rules for the EXPRESS language. NamedTypes, Algorithms, Constants, and "SupertypeRules" can be defined at the Schema level or within Algorithms and GlobalRules. The CommonElements whose Scope is a Schema are SchemaElements; the others are LocalElements.

represents the relationship between a CommonElement and the "scope" in which it is defined; also, the scope (set of model elements) in which the id of the CommonElement refers to that CommonElement.

See Clause 10 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a NamedElement whose scope is a Schema, an independent model element. Every kind of CommonElement can be a SchemaElement, but only some CommonElement instances are SchemaElements, and some kinds of SchemaElements are not CommonElements.
refines NamedElement.id. The identifier for a NamedElement whose Scope is a Schema is a SchemaScopeId.

represents the relationship between the SchemaElement and the Schema in which it is (originally) defined. refines NamedElement.namespace

See 9.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between the Schema and the SchemaElements that are defined in it, as distinct from those that are interfaced into it. refines the Scope.named-elements relationship.

See 9.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
A ScopedId whose namespace is the LocalScope in which it is declared. It is visible only in that LocalScope.
a refinement of Scope.terms, represents the collection of terms that are defined in a given LocalScope.
a refinement of ScopedId.namespace, represents the relationship between a LocalId and the LocalScope that is its namespace.
An abstract type representing the combination of an Identifier and its namespace, which together constitute a well-defined symbol for an EXPRESS ModelElement.
represents the relationship between a Scope and the terms that are defined within it.
represents the relationship between a ScopedId (term) and the Scope object that is the namespace in which that ScopedId refers to whatever it identifies.
A CommonScope that is also a LocalScope, or equivalently, a CommonScope that is not a Schema.
A Scope in which CommonElements can be declared. A CommonScope is either a Schema or an AlgorithmScope.

represents the EXPRESS "interface" relationships (USE, REFERENCE) between an interfacing Schema and the SchemaElements that it interfaces from the Schema in which they are defined.

See clause 11 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

the new Identifier for the SchemaElement in the interfacing schema.

True if the interfacing statement is USE; False otherwise. isUSE can only be True if the interfaced SchemaElement is a NamedType.

the Schema that contains the USE, REFERENCE interface statement that directly or indirectly referred to the interfaced SchemaElement. A given SchemaElement can be interfaced into (referenced-in) 0 or more Schemas.

represents the SchemaElement interfaced by a schema-interfaces-elements relationship. A given Schema can interface any number of SchemaElements from any number of other Schemas, but it interfaces any given element exactly once.
This is the relationship represented by the (Association)Class schema-interfaces-elements.
a principal concept of the EXPRESS language, an object that is defined in a model, has a notion of "lifetime", and has an identifier that refers to it in Schemas or in some nested Scope in a Schema.

represents the relationship between a Scope and the NamedElements that are defined in it

represents the relationship between a NamedElement and the "scope" in which it is defined, i.e. the set of model elements for which that name refers to that NamedElement

is True if the Remark is lexically a Tail Remark; and False if the Remark is lexically an Embedded remark

Represents the actual text of the remark. Note: Part 11 requires that the character set of the remark be the EXPRESS character set, but in practice a larger subset of ISO 10646-1 Basic Multilingual Plane is often used.

See 7.1.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between a NamedElement and the Remarks, if any, that constitute its in-schema documentation. If the Scope (.appears-in) of the Remark is, or is contained in, a different Schema from the declaration of the NamedElement, the Remark only applies to the NamedElement as-interfaced.

See 7.1.6.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between a Remark and the NamedElement(s) it describes. While a tagged remark is formally associated with one or more NamedElement(s), a processor may also ascribe a given un-tagged Remark to a given NamedElement, based on its lexical position.

See 7.1.6.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between a Schema and the Remarks, if any, that constitute its in-schema documentation. If the Scope (.appears-in) of the Remark is a different Schema, the Remark only applies to the Schema as-interfaced.

See 7.1.6.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004. Technically the Schema is a named element of the EXPRESS language, but it has no defined Scope.

represents the relationship between a Remark that describes a Schema and the Schema it describes. The Remark may be Tagged to refer to the Schema, or it may be ascribed to the Schema if it lacks any other association. In particular, a Remark may appear in one Schema and refer to an interfaced Schema or to elements interfaced from it.

See 7.1.6.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004. Technically the Schema is a named element of the EXPRESS language, but it has no defined Scope.

represents the relationship between a Schema and the Remarks that appear in it.

See 7.1.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
represents the relationship of a Remark to the Schema that lexically contains it.
generalized relationship of a data type to the schemas in which it is defined.
generalized relationship of the Schema to the data types defined in it.

a constraint requiring all of its operands to be mutually exclusive. Each operand can be a single Extent or a union of Extents.

represents the inclusion of a FunctionBody that defines the values of Variables that are local to the GlobalRule. The supporting-body exists if and only if the GlobalRule defines one or more local Variables.

a constraint requiring a given Boolean Expression involving the Extents of one or more EntityTypes to evaluate to True. It corresponds to a domain rule contained in a Rule declaration in EXPRESS.

See 9.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

the local identifier, if any, for the NamedRule. It is NamedElement.id, but its Scope is the GlobalRule.

See 9.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
Represents the lexical position of the NamedRule in the sequence of NamedRules contained in the GlobalRule.

represents the relationship between the NamedRule and the GlobalRule that contains it. In addition to being the namespace for the id of the NamedRule, the GlobalRule identifies the EntityTypes to which the NamedRule applies (and whose Extents may be referred to in the asserted-expression) and may define Variables that are used in the asserted-expression.

represents the relationship between the GlobalRule (container) and the NamedRules it contains. Since the GlobalRule also constitutes the scope of the id (if any) for the NamedRule, this relationship is treated as a specialization of the Scope.named-elements relationship.
represents the relationship between a SupertypeRule (supertype-clause or SUBTYPE_CONSTRAINT) and the individual subtype constraints it contains.
represents the relationship of a SubtypeConstraint to the SupertypeRule that contains it, which also identifies the common supertype.

represents the fact that every SubtypeConstraint is equivalent to a BooleanExpression involving the Extents of the EntityTypes named in the SubtypeConstraint. The Expression is required to evaluate to True.

a collection of rules requiring specific relationships among the Extents of two or more subtypes of a given supertype EntityType. The constraint can be stated as a relationship among the Extents as Sets of entity instances. SupertypeRule corresponds to a SUBTYPE_CONSTRAINT declaration, or to the EXPRESS supertype-clause attached to an entity declaration.

See 9.2.5 and 9.7 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

the identifier, if any, for the SupertypeRule. It is NamedElement.identifier. It is used only to control interfacing of SUBTYPE_CONSTRAINT Rules. SupertypeRules stated in supertype-expressions never have identifiers; SupertypeRules stated as SUBTYPE_CONSTRAINTS always do.

See 9.7 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a SchemaElement denoting a collection of NamedRules for the interaction of the Extents of one or more EntityTypes. It corresponds to the RULE declaration in EXPRESS. Every GlobalRule is also an AlgorithmScope and may define CommonElements and Variables.

See 9.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

Represents the identifier for the GlobalRule. It is NamedElement.id, but it is mandatory, and its Scope is the Schema in which it is defined or interfaced.

See 9.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between an Extent (within a Population) and the EntityInstances it contains. Extent is a SetValue and Extent.content is just the relationship between that SetValue and its members.
represents any InstantiableType that is not a NamedType.

a NamedType representing an EXPRESS entity data type, a type declared by an entity_declaration.

See 9.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

True if the EXPRESS entity data type is declared ABSTRACT, by any of: ABSTRACT entity, ABSTRACT SUPERTYPE, or SUBTYPE_CONSTRAINT ABSTRACT; False otherwise.

See 9.2.4 and 9.2.5.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a NamedType representing an EXPRESS defined data type, a type declared by a type_declaration.

See 8.3.2 and 9.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an AnonymousType representing an EXPRESS "aggregation type", whose instances are collections of instances of a "member type": ARRAY, BAG, LIST, SET.

True if the members of a given value of the type are required to be distinct; else False. isUnique is always True for a SET type, always False for a BAG type, and True for LIST and ARRAY types if and only if the UNIQUE keyword is present in the type designation

See 8.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an AnonymousType representing those EXPRESS data types defined in the language as "simple types": BINARY types, BOOLEAN, INTEGER, LOGICAL, NUMBER, REAL types, and STRING types.

See 8.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the EXPRESS keyword denoting the SimpleType, one of: BINARY, BOOLEAN, INTEGER, LOGICAL, NUMBER, REAL, STRING.

See 8.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents any InstantiableType that is not an EntityType

See 9.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a DefinedType representing an EXPRESS defined data type whose underlying_type is a SELECT data type.

represents a constraint on the extensions of an Extensible SelectType: True if every NamedType in the extension must be an EntityType; otherwise False..

True if the SelectType is EXTENSIBLE, i.e. if it can have additional NamedTypes in the select-list when it is interfaced into another Schema; False otherwise.

See 8.4.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
represents the relationship of an AggregationType to the data type of its components (members).

represents the EXPRESS "specialization" relationship between a ConcreteType and a defined data type that uses the same value representations.

represents the EXPRESS "specialization" relationship between a defined data type and the "underlying type" used to represent it.

See 9.1 and 9.7 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the appearance of the "generalizes" NamedType in the select list of the "instantiates" SelectType.

See 8.4.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between the NamedType and a SelectType whose domain includes it.

See 8.4.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an abstract classifier, representing those "data-type-like" descriptors that are really conformance rules for possible InstantiableTypes. These types are only permitted as the data type of formal parameters and the data type of "abstract" Attributes of ABSTRACT EntityTypes. GeneralizedType is a proper subclass of DataType.

represents the relationship of an extended select type to the (extensible) select type it is BASED ON.

See 8.4.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship of an EXTENSIBLE select type to a select type BASED ON it.

See 8.4.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
represents the relationship between the domain constraint and a Boolean expression that can be evaluated to determine if it holds.

represents the relationship of an AnonymousType to a subtype ("specialization") of it, as specified in Part 11 clause 9.2.7. Unlike the specialization for defined data types, these relationships are true subtypes: the domain of the "specialization" is a subset of the domain of AnonymousType and has the same interpretation.
represents the relationship of an AnonymousType to an AnonymousType of which it is a "specialization", as specified in Part 11 clause 9.2.7.

represents all EXPRESS REAL data types, which are distinguished from one another by different values of "precision". Type REAL (with no "precision" value) is one instance of REALType.

See 8.1.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the number of significant figures in the values of the RealType, as specified in its syntactic designation. Although the value of "precision" is specified in EXPRESS to be an expression, it is assumed in this model that the value will in practice be a "constant". The only REALType for which "precision" is not present is the EXPRESS type REAL (with no precision specification).

See 8.1.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a SimpleType representing all EXPRESS STRING data types, which are distinguished by different LengthConstraints. By definition, every EXPRESS STRING type with a LengthConstraint is different from every other STRING data type. (They may be compatible with others, but not the same.) The only instance of STRINGType with no LengthConstraint is the EXPRESS data type STRING.

See 8.1.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a SimpleType representing all EXPRESS BINARY data types, which are distinguished by different LengthConstraints. By definition, every EXPRESS BINARY type with a LengthConstraint is different from every other BINARY data type. (They may be compatible with others, but not the same.) The only instance of BINARYType with no LengthConstraint is the EXPRESS data type BINARY.

See 8.1.7 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents any maximum-length or fixed-length constraint on the length of the values of a STRING or BINARY type. A LengthConstraint is a DomainConstraint, considered to have an equivalent Boolean expression using the built-in Length() function.

See 8.1.6 and 8.1.7 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents a constant value specifying the required maximum/fixed length of the STRING or BINARY value. This attribute is present when the constraint expression is a "constant".

See 8.1.6 and 8.1.9 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

True if all values of the SimpleType are required to be of the same length; False if the constraint specifies only the maximum length of the values.

See 8.1.6 and 8.1.8 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents a constraint on the length (in characters) of the values in the domain of the STRING data type.

See 8.1.6 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents a constraint on the length (in bits) of the values in the domain of the BINARY data type

See 8.1.7 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an abstract classifier, encompassing all the data type notions that characterize objects and properties in EXPRESS. InstantiableType is a proper subtype of DataType (which includes classifiers that represent conformance rules for InstantiableTypes).

See 8.6.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

a SchemaElement that defines a new InstantiableType.

the unique identifier for the NamedType. It is NamedElement.id, but it is mandatory, and its Scope is the Schema in which it is defined or interfaced, or the Algorithm or Rule in which it is declared.

See 8.3 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an AggregationType representing all EXPRESS SET data types.

See 8.2.4 of ISO 10303-11:2004.
an AggregationType representing all EXPRESS ARRAY data types.

True if the member type is declared to be OPTIONAL in the syntactic designation for the ARRAYType; False otherwise. When isOptional is True, any instance of the ARRAYType is permitted to have members whose value is unspecified ('?').

See 8.2.1 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an AggregationType representing all EXPRESS LIST data types

See 8.2.2 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

an AggregationType representing all EXPRESS BAG data types

represents the appearance of an upper-bound constraint in syntactic designation for the aggregation type. For this purpose the appearance of an explicit indeterminate value ('?') is considered to represent no upper-bound constraint, and shall not be represented by an upper-bound relationship. (The appearance of an upper-bound expression that may evaluate to '?' shall be represented by an upper-bound relationship.)

See 8.2.x of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between the ARRAYType and the upper bound on the Integer index-range of each value of the ARRAYType.

represents the appearance of a lower-bound constraint in syntactic designation for the aggregation type. (The appearance of a lower-bound expression that may evaluate to zero shall always be represented by a lower-bound relationship.)

See 8.2.x of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents any constraint on the number of members in each value of an EXPRESS aggregation type that appears in the syntactic designation for the type. A SizeConstraint represents either an upper-bound or a lower-bound; in the case of an ARRAY type, the value (hi-index - lo-index + 1) is both the lower-bound value and the upper-bound value. A SizeConstraint is a DomainConstraint, considered to have an equivalent Boolean expression using the built-in SizeOf() function.

See 8.2.2, 8.2.3, and 8.2.4 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents a constant value specifying the (upper or lower) bound on the number of members in a valid instance of the aggregation type. This attribute is present when the bound expression is a "constant".

See 8.2.2, 8.2.3, and 8.2.4 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

represents the relationship between an EntityType and the declared Attributes of that EntityType, including those in the entity declaration and those inherited from supertypes.

the Expression that specifies how to determine the value of the DerivedAttribute from the values of other Attributes.

represents an upper-bound constraint on the size of values of the AGGREGATE type. the definition of an Algorithm as a sequence of actions to be performed.

the formal description of an operand of a Procedure or Function.

the name used to identify the Parameter within the FunctionBody. It is NamedElement.identifier, but it is mandatory.

a constraint that requires an identity relationship between the ActualTypes derived from the actual parameters corresponding to two distinct Parameters to an Algorithm. It is denoted in EXPRESS by the type_tag on a generalized_type. The ActualTypeConstraint refers to one pair of Parameters whose formal parameter types contain the same type_tag. If there is only one such Parameter, there is no ActualTypeConstraint. If there are more than two such Parameters, each possible pair constitutes a distinct ActualTypeConstraint.

See 9.5.3.4 of ISO 10303-11:2004.

the type_tag on a generalized_type that denotes the requirement for identity of all actual types corresponding to the generalized_type with this tag. In effect, it names the constraint.

represents the relationship between a Parameter and the Algorithm that owns it.

represents the relationship between an Algorithm and its formal Parameters.

represents the relationship between the LocalScope and the set of Variables that are defined within it.

represents the relationship between the Variable and the LocalScope in which it is defined. This is a refinement of the NamedElement.namespace relationship. Unlike many other NamedElements, the lifetime of a Variable is exactly equal to the lifetime of the instance having the LocalScope.

represents the relationship between a FunctionResult and the Function that produces it.

represents the relationship between a Function and its FunctionResult.

represents the Data Type specification for the formal parameter. It can specify an InstantiableType of which the actual parameter value must be a valid Instance, or a GeneralizedType to which the InstantiableType of the actual parameter must conform.

an Algorithm that returns a single Instance and can appear in an Expression.

an Algorithm that is executed as an action in a FunctionBody.

a CommonElement that represents an operation or process that transforms information. Every Algorithm is either a Procedure or a Function. Every Algorithm is also an AlgorithmScope, in that it may define CommonElements and local ModelElements.

specification of an actual data type by reference to (a component of) the actual data type of a Parameter. It is denoted in EXPRESS by the type_tag on a generalized_type. But an ActualType is uniquely identified within an Algorithm scope by the tag and the Parameter to which it refers.

represents the relationship between an Algorithm and the set of ActualTypeConstraints that apply to its formal parameters.

represents the value resulting from evaluating the value-expression. This value may only be computable for a given population, or it may require computational capabilities a given agent does not have.

an ExpressionType that represents all the data type notions that can be declared for objects and properties in EXPRESS. Syntactically called parameter_type, it includes InstantiableTypes and GeneralizedTypes (which represent conformance rules for InstantiableTypes). It excludes PartialEntityTypes, which are only classifiers for intermediate results.

represents any real or conceptual object, information unit or data item.

represents the relationship between a DataType and the Instances that satisfy it.
represents an Expression with an unparsed EXPRESS text corpus.
